---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import Terminal from '../../components/Terminal.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Pin Caps"
  description="Pin caps bound what an agent can touch. Tier sets the floor; pin profiles add ceilings. Four operator problems and the compositions that solve them."
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-8">
    Pin caps are the policy layer between identity and audit. Tier sets the floor (you can't write past it); custom pin profiles add ceilings on top. The merge is union of denies — pins never relax tier defaults.
  </p>

  <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    Pin caps are evaluated at every write through the tool layer. They live at <code class="text-primary">.ostk/pins/&lt;name&gt;/pin.caps</code>; the active profile is selected by <code class="text-primary">OSTK_PIN</code> env var, or falls back to the tier-default. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/serve/policy.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/file.rs</code>.
  </p>

  <!-- Problem 01 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_01 // DEFAULT_BY_TIER</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">I haven't written any pin caps. What does an agent get by default?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Whatever your tier-default pin allows. The kernel resolves your trust tier at boot (T0/T1/T2/T3 — see <a href="/docs/trust-model" class="text-primary hover:underline">trust model</a>) and applies the matching default profile. T0 is unrestricted; T1 denies <code class="text-primary">write-kernel</code> and <code class="text-primary">modify-governance</code>; T2 also denies <code class="text-primary">write-src</code>; T3 denies all writes. You start safe, then opt into more permissive pins as needed.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 max-w-2xl mb-3">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4 font-body text-xs border-b border-surface-variant pb-2 mb-3">
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-secondary">TIER</div>
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-secondary">WRITES_ALLOWED</div>
        <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary">DEFAULT_DENIES</div>
      </div>
      {[
        { tier: 'T0', write: 'unrestricted', denies: '(none — full governance)' },
        { tier: 'T1', write: 'project source', denies: 'write-kernel, modify-governance' },
        { tier: 'T2', write: 'narrow', denies: 'write-kernel, modify-governance, write-src' },
        { tier: 'T3', write: 'none', denies: 'ALL writes (allows_write=false)' },
      ].map(row => (
        <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4 font-body text-xs py-2 border-b border-surface-variant">
          <div class="text-on-surface font-bold">{row.tier}</div>
          <div class="text-secondary">{row.write}</div>
          <div class="text-secondary">{row.denies}</div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Tier resolver (boot-time GPG check) · tier-default pin profile · pin caps evaluator at every write · Owned State (invariant II) — the kernel decides, no operator override.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/identity.rs</code> (tier resolver), <code class="text-primary">src/serve/policy.rs</code> (pin caps evaluator), <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/file.rs</code> (write-time enforcement).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 02 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_02 // BOUND_A_WORKER</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">I want a fix-bug worker to touch <code>src/</code> but not <code>infra/</code> or <code>secrets/</code>.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Three steps. <code class="text-primary">ostk issue_pin fix-bug</code> creates a profile at <code class="text-primary">.ostk/pins/fix-bug/pin.caps</code> and a tack-script at <code class="text-primary">pin.boot</code>. Edit the caps file: list the deny tokens (path-scoped) and any deny-verb lines. Reference the profile from the worker — set <code class="text-primary">OSTK_PIN=fix-bug</code> in the Agentfile or env. Every write through the kernel checks the active profile before bytes hit disk.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk issue_pin fix-bug
created: .ostk/pins/fix-bug/pin.caps
created: .ostk/pins/fix-bug/pin.boot

<span class="text-outline">$ </span>cat .ostk/pins/fix-bug/pin.caps
<span class="text-error">deny:</span> write-kernel modify-governance
<span class="text-error">deny-path:</span> infra/ secrets/ .env*
<span class="text-error">deny-verb:</span> :shutdown
<span class="text-error">deny-verb:</span> bail pack --private

<span class="text-outline"># Apply to the worker:</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>OSTK_PIN=fix-bug ostk run .ostk/agents/fix-bug-27.toml</pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <code class="text-primary">issue_pin</code> command · pin.caps file format (deny tokens, deny-path, deny-verb) · <code class="text-primary">OSTK_PIN</code> env var selects active profile · merge with tier-default at evaluator time.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/issue_pin.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/serve/policy.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 03 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_03 // MERGE_ORDER</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">My pin tries to permit <code>write-src</code> but the agent still gets denied. Why?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Pin caps are <strong class="text-on-surface">attenuation only</strong>. The kernel takes the union of deny tokens — your tier-default's denies plus your custom profile's denies. A pin can <em>add</em> restrictions but cannot <em>remove</em> them. A T2 user setting <code class="text-primary">OSTK_PIN=permissive</code> still gets <code class="text-primary">write-src</code> denied because T2's tier-default contains it. Tier is the floor; pins are extra ceiling.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 max-w-2xl mb-3 font-body text-xs leading-relaxed">
      <div class="text-secondary mb-3">Worked example for a T2 operator with custom pin <code class="text-primary">"infra-eng"</code>:</div>
      <pre class="text-outline mb-3"><span class="text-secondary">tier-default (T2):</span> deny: write-kernel modify-governance write-src
<span class="text-secondary">infra-eng pin:</span>     deny: write-kernel deny-path: secrets/
                          (no allow lines — pins can't have them)
<span class="text-secondary">union (effective):</span> deny: write-kernel modify-governance write-src
                          deny-path: secrets/</pre>
      <div class="text-secondary">The agent gets <strong class="text-on-surface">strictly more</strong> restrictive — write-src denied (from tier) plus secrets/ denied (from pin). To unlock write-src, the operator has to graduate to T1 — that's the whole point of the trust ladder.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Tier-default (floor) + custom pin (ceiling) → union of denies → final cap set. Attenuation-only merge semantics; pins never relax tier defaults.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/serve/attenuation.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/serve/policy.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 04 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_04 // DISCOVER_THE_RIGHT_PINS</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">I don't know what paths my worker actually needs. How do I find the minimal pin?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      <code class="text-primary">ostk learn</code> runs the worker in observation mode — it watches every filesystem call the agent makes and emits the minimal set of <code class="text-primary">LIMIT</code> directives that would have permitted that run. You read the directives, decide what to keep, drop into the Agentfile or pin.caps. Empirical bounding instead of guesswork. The technique generalizes: run learn over your representative tasks; compare the union of paths; pin accordingly.
    </p>

    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline"># Run the worker under observation (60s default, --duration overrides)</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk learn .ostk/agents/fix-bug-27.toml --duration 120

<span class="text-outline"># Output: minimal LIMIT directives the agent actually needed</span>
<span class="text-secondary">LIMIT</span> read-path src/ tests/ Cargo.toml
<span class="text-secondary">LIMIT</span> write-path src/ tests/ target/
<span class="text-secondary">LIMIT</span> verb cargo build cargo test

<span class="text-outline"># --apply writes them back into the Agentfile directly</span>
<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk learn .ostk/agents/fix-bug-27.toml --apply</pre>
    </Terminal>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mt-4 mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Observe mode (nono sandbox in passthrough-with-logging) · path-set extraction from observed syscalls · <code class="text-primary">LIMIT</code> directive emission · optional <code class="text-primary">--apply</code> to write back to the Agentfile.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/commands/learn.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/sandbox.rs</code> (observation mode).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The composition -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">THE_COMPOSITION</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Tier sets the floor. Pins add ceilings. The kernel evaluates.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-6">
      Three primitives compose into the answer for "what can this agent actually do?" — your tier-default pin from the GPG trust check (the floor; can't relax), your custom pin profile selected by <code class="text-primary">OSTK_PIN</code> (the ceiling; only adds restrictions), and the evaluator that checks every write at the tool layer before bytes hit disk. Combined with the OS-level sandbox covered in <a href="/docs/architecture#problem_02_agent_tries_to_escape" class="text-primary hover:underline">architecture problem 02</a>, that's three layers of defense for every kernel-mediated action.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-lowest p-4 border border-surface-variant max-w-2xl mb-4 font-body text-xs">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">CAPABILITY_TOKENS_REFERENCE</div>
      <div class="space-y-1 text-secondary">
        <div><code class="text-error">deny: write-kernel</code> &mdash; all writes under <code class="text-primary">.ostk/</code></div>
        <div><code class="text-error">deny: modify-governance</code> &mdash; <code class="text-primary">.primefile</code>, <code class="text-primary">GOVERNANCE.md</code>, <code class="text-primary">ENTITYFILE</code>, HUMANFILE, Agentfiles</div>
        <div><code class="text-error">deny: write-src</code> &mdash; project source files</div>
        <div><code class="text-error">deny-path: &lt;path&gt;</code> &mdash; literal or prefix-match path block</div>
        <div><code class="text-error">deny-verb: &lt;cmd&gt;</code> &mdash; exact or prefix-match command block</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline max-w-xl">
      Pin profiles are the per-worker knob. Tier defaults are the per-operator floor. The trust model determines tier; the operator authors profiles; the evaluator merges and enforces. None of the three is load-bearing on its own.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="metadata-ribbon border-t border-surface-variant">
    <span class="font-label text-[10px] text-secondary mr-4">RELATED:</span>
